# Extract features and target variable
features = data.iloc[:, 13:]

In [5]:
# Split the data into train and test sets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(features, target, test_size = 0.33, random_state = 42)

# Initialize the StandardScaler
scaler = StandardScaler()

# Fit and transform the scaler on your features
X_train_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test_scaled = scaler.transform(X_test)

# Create LassoLarsCV model
lasso_lars_cv = LassoLarsCV(cv=5)
lasso_lars_cv.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train)

print("Optimal alpha:", lasso_lars_cv.alpha_)
print("Lasso Coefficients:")
for feature, coef in zip(features.columns, lasso_lars_cv.coef_):
    if coef != 0:
        print(f"{feature}: {coef:.10f}")

# Predict using the LassoLarsCV model with the optimal alpha on the test set
lasso_lars_predictions = lasso_lars_cv.predict(X_test_scaled)

# Calculate the Mean Squared Error on the test set
mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, lasso_lars_predictions)
print("Mean Squared Error on Test Set:", mse)

# Extract the intercept and coefficients
intercept = lasso_lars_cv.intercept_
coefficients = lasso_lars_cv.coef_

# Calculate the predicted LogKsw values using the linear regression equation on the test set
predicted_logksw = np.dot(X_test_scaled, coefficients) + intercept

# Get the non-zero coefficients and their corresponding feature names
non_zero_coeffs = lasso_lars_cv.coef_
selected_features = features.columns[non_zero_coeffs != 0]
selected_coeffs = non_zero_coeffs[non_zero_coeffs != 0]

# Sort the coefficients and feature names by magnitude
sorted_indices = selected_coeffs.argsort()
sorted_coeffs = selected_coeffs[sorted_indices]
sorted_features = selected_features[sorted_indices]

# Create a vertical bar plot
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))

# Compute the LARS Lasso path
alphas, _, coefs = lars_path(X_train_scaled, y_train, method='lasso')

# Normalize the coefficients
coefs /= np.max(np.abs(coefs), axis=0)

# Specify a colormap
cmap = plt.get_cmap('plasma')

# Plot the LARS Lasso path
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 7))
lines = plt.plot(alphas, coefs.T, alpha = 0.7)
plt.vlines(lasso_lars_cv.alpha_, ymin=-1, ymax=1, linestyle='dashed', colors='#041b15', label='Optimal Alpha', linewidth=2.5)
plt.xlabel('Alpha')
plt.ylabel('Normalized Coefficients')
plt.title('LARS Lasso Path for LogKsw Prediction')
plt.legend()

# Apply the colormap to the lines
for line, color in zip(lines, cmap(np.linspace(0, 1, len(features.columns)))):
    line.set_color(color)

plt.axis('tight')
plt.show()
